org.mindswap.owls.process
Interface Process

All Superinterfaces:
MultiConditional, OWLEntity, OWLIndividual, OWLObject, OWLValue
All Known Subinterfaces:
AtomicProcess, CompositeProcess, SimpleProcess
All Known Implementing Classes:
AtomicProcessImpl, CompositeProcessImpl, ProcessImpl, SimpleProcessImpl
public interface Process
extends OWLIndividual, MultiConditional

Abstract representation of OWL-S processes. A process can be either a atomic, composite, or a simple process. Properties that all three process types share are defined here.

Corresponding OWL-S concept: org.mindswap.owls.vocabulary.OWLS.Process#Process.

getService

Service getService()
Get the service this process belongs to. Actually a process may be used in multiple service descriptions. Unfortunately, OWL-S 1.0 specification does not make a distinction between process definition and process occurrence. This implementation treats each process object as a process occurrence and returns the service object this process is used in.

Returns:
the service to which this process is bound

removeService

void removeService()
Removes the service from this process by breaking the link service:describes. The service itself remains untouched.

getProfile

Profile getProfile()
Returns:
The profile for the service of this process. This is equivalent to getService().getProfile().

prepare

Process prepare(ExecutionContext context)
Prepare this process for subsequent execution. Implementations may set up means to optimize execution in terms of whatever resources, e.g., space and time. However, support of this operation is a optional, hence, implementations may do nothing.

Parameters:
context - Any kind of context information to support preparation.
Returns:
The prepared process. Implementations may return the same (but prepared) object instance (this) or a new process instance, just as they like.

getDataFlow

ProcessDataFlow getDataFlow(OWLOntology dfOntology)
This method analyzes the data flow defined by this process and returns a representation of it using the producer-push convention (rather than the consumer-pull convention of OWL-S). The producer-push convention is realized through properties defined in OWLS_Extensions.

Only composite processes can actually have a data flow, whereas atomic processes do not have a data flow as they can not be further decomposed.

Note that this operation may be costly, depending on the size of the process. Consequently, implementations should provide means to optimize repeated invocations of this method (e.g., by means of internal caches).

Parameters:
dfOntology - The backing ontology which will be enriched by the the producer-push data flow representation. Can be left null to create and use a new one (which will belong the associated KB).
Returns:
The data flow structure represented by this process.
